8\. Taxonomy Evolution

The taxonomy is a living artifact. Pension administration reveals edge
cases that no upfront analysis can anticipate. When a defect does not
fit the existing categories, the taxonomy must evolve rather than
forcing a misclassification.

8.1 Taxonomy Change Process

9.  **Identification:** A defect is encountered that does not clearly
    fit any existing category. The classifier assigns the closest
    category and flags it as "category fit: poor" in the defect record.

10. **Accumulation:** When three or more defects are flagged with poor
    category fit in the same pattern, a taxonomy revision is proposed.

11. **Proposal:** The proposal defines: the new category name and
    3-letter code, its precise definition, at least two examples, the
    resolution path, and the relationship to existing categories (is it
    a split of an existing category, or genuinely new?).

12. **Review:** Technical Director reviews and approves. The taxonomy
    change is treated as a documentation change with version increment.

13. **Propagation:** All five layer documents are updated to reference
    the new category. The dashboard is updated to display it. Any
    misclassified defects are reclassified.

8.2 Taxonomy Versioning

The taxonomy carries a version number (currently v1.0). Every change to
categories, severity definitions, scope definitions, priority matrix, or
metric definitions increments the version. Defect records store the
taxonomy version under which they were classified. If the taxonomy
changes, previously classified defects are not retroactively
reclassified unless the change specifically addresses a known
misclassification pattern.

9\. Complete Document Map

The five-layer defect management system is now complete. This section
maps every artifact to its owner, purpose, and cross-references.

